This Eucalyptus wilcoxii mallee has been badly burnt in the January 2020 fire. It is re-sprouting from the base.
Found off Mistake Fire-trail, atop a rock-face, above a tributary of Desert Creek.

Location is approximate on top of Numbugga Walls.  I did not take a whole of plant shot on this occasion, but the bud shape is distinctive for E. wilcoxii - buds in 3s, with a little nipple on the tip of the operculum. This species is scattered on cliffs in the Desert Creek catchment, where its bronze coloured bark and finer foliage distinguishes it from the co-occurring mallee E. spectatrix.

Growing on conglomerate cliffs above the Brogo Dam. The bronze bark and narrow grey-green foliage help confirm the ID of this species.  It is a mallee, but some stems can be quite large on plants growing in a decent amount of soil.

This photo was taken in 2004, after the extreme drought of the 2002-03 summer and the resprouting occurring on these E. wilcoxii would be post-drought rather than post-fire.  These mallees are very hardy, growing as they do in almost no soil, but many suffered dieback during the millenium drought.

Jan 2020 fire impacts on cliffs to S of Brogo River & west of the dam, an area I did not think had burnt. On boating up the dam I found some ridges had burnt, with fire seemingly running downslope to the dam (near-dry at the time) in spots.  At this location it looks like the fire burnt patchily down the cliff face, with the Euc agglomerata on the left and Acacia georgensis on the right unaffected, but the Euc wilcoxii between them burnt. Some thin blackened mallee stems do not appear to be resprouting (possibly dead from drought pre-fire), but the dense grey-green foliage in the middle of the photo is basal resprouting from the lignotuber on the part of E. wilcoxii.  This plant is not listed as threatened, but it does have quite a restricted distribution, much of which would have burnt in either 2018 or 2020 fires.

- Distribution: NSW
- Distribution by botanical region: Central Western Slopes
- Habit: Tree
- Bark persistence of type: Partly rough
- Rough bark type: Loose basal slabs
- Number of buds or flowers per umbel: seven-flowered
- Flower bud shape: Spindle-shaped
- Flower bud glaucescence: Glaucous (Seemed as though new buds would not have wax but then after being on the tree a short time would gain wax? Photos show both in the same picture so happy to be told that's not the right understanding)
- Juvenile leaf blade shape: Ovate, elliptical or oblong
- Juvenile leaf base shape: Tapering to petiole

description:
Small sapling of a type of Eucalyptus not readily apparent in tree form in the area concerned. Myponga Reservoir walk. Most of the nearby bigger gums were Eucalyptus camaldulensis camaldulensis, Eucalyptus leucoxylon leucoxylon and Eucalyptus fasciculosa but the area was cleared for farming long before the dam was built resulting in inundation of much of the cleared land in what was once known as Lovely Valley. The approach to Myponga town via Main South Rd from Sellicks Hill still contains some roadside original selfset mature Eucalyptus viminalis ssp cygnetensis ,and I think the above sapling is an example of that species, but less likely that subspecies. Several other possibilities exist including E viminalis viminalis (potentially naturally occurring ,as it does in the wetter parts of the Fleurieu Peninsula eg 
Inman Valley and if I recall correctly the Myponga area itself,alternatively as tubestock  planted by Woods and Forests staff and/or SA Water staff many decades ago, either amenity planting or trial forestry planting).
Finally there may be some White Gum  relict specimens among the denser groves of River Red Gum that-as already noted- are a major feature of the remaining treed areas surrounding the Reservoir (apart from the plantation Pinus radiata, obviously).

Bark hard (ironbark), dark grey, deeply and coarsely furrowed, persistent to small branches. 
Adult leaves narrow-lanceolate to lanceolate, alternate, acuminate, petiolate, ~15 x 1.5 cm wide, concolorous, bluish-green, dull, densely reticulate. 
~10 white flowers on slender peduncles ~12 mm long. 
Buds relatively small ~9mm x 4mm, clavate to diamond-shaped, scar present, operculum conical to hemispherical. 
Fruit small ~6mm x 4mm across with thin rim and disc descending, cupular, pedicellate.  

Apologies for the poor quality (out-of-focus) bud shots.

Edit - the operculum is distinctly shorter and narrower than the floral tube/buds are broadest at the rim. Special thanks to Margaretjb for pointing out this crucial distinguishing feature, as I had originally mistaken this obs for E. crebra.

description: There are two trees in this location which appear to be the original remaining trees that were in the grounds of the school that was located here. They support the feeding of the rainbow lorikeets feeding on nearby lemon gums

Unlike most of the mallee gums at this roadside location this one was heavily laden with flower buds but not yet any flowers. (The other mallee gums here had similar small narrow shiny leaves but very few bore any flower buds, nor any retained nuts on the branches and branchlets. However my guess is that the current observation is probably the same species as the great majority of the other mallee trees nearby..And this mallee, as with the others, bore no mature nuts on the branches and branchlets. (The above comments do not apply to the only other distinct eucalyptus species  at this location-E.porosa-which as a mallee box is considered separately from the  above more typical mallee gums here).

All images are of one tree. I had to pick a sprig of fresh erect growth from within reach and image it laid on the ground because there were no gumnuts on lower branches amenable to in situ photos.The gumnuts were very small.  This mallee species(or perhaps several, intergrading??) is dominant at this roadside location but very few of the many such trees bore any nuts at all that I could see  even towards the canopies. Happily there were a few exceptions. The species has uniformly small thin leaves, tending erect, and varying from shiny green to grey green but mostly the first. Most trees have short basal stockings of rough bark grading quickly to smooth cream bark with scanty decorticating strips. However some trunks retain the rough, tessellated dark grey bark to heights of 2-3 metres or more. On the same mature mallee tree one might see a mix of almost entirely smooth barked main branches and ones of equal thickness and size with the rough bark persistent almost to the branchlets.

description:
This plant is in the Myrtaceae family because it is a woody plant containing aromatically scented oils. 
It is in the genus Eucalyptus based on its layered bark type and oil glands in the leaves. 
I’ve identified it as Eucalyptus cinerea based on its rounded leaf shape and the colouration of the bark (red/brown). 
Other possible examples include Eucalyptus pantoleuca but I have excluded this due to it being endemic to the Kimberly (WA) and it’s trunk width and bark type (smooth).

description: I have identified this plant as a Eucalyptus pauciflour because of its distinctive white, grey and yellow back and its clavate buds and lanceolate leaves.
regrowth after fire

This species, I knew was in the family Myrtaceae due to the signature aromatic leaves.
Using the Robinson guide I was able to determine the genus as Eucalyptus due to its smooth bark and drooping, alternate, leathery leaves.
Determining the species was a little more tricky, however, the distinct moth larvae “scribbles” meant it was either racemosa or haemastoma (not sclerophylla due to location). Referencing PlantNet, I chose haemastoma over racemosa as the leaves were greater than 1.5cm wide. The trunk at the base had been burned leaving a significant cavity which I found interesting.

Media reports from 2019 state that the Peregian Springs area experienced fires during both September and December. The site is close to residences where evacuations were carried out on those occasions. 
This location is about 3.5 kms west of Peregian Beach.

description: 3 pics of tesselated rough bark and resprouting juvenile foliage at the base of a mature tree beside the walking track from car park to Ingalla Falls. Similar trees are the dominant feature of this open canopy wet  sclerophyll woodland on much of the steep slopes forming each side of the gully. There is a thin line of closed canopy riparian corridor habitat along the gully floor but the Blackwood wattles in effect  become the canopy along this very moist creekline. There is taller closed canopy wet sclerophyll forest focally opposite the entrance car park but that is courtesy of the planted Eucalyptus viminalis ssp viminalis, which in all probability was derived from manna gums from outside the district (perhaps Stirling or Inman Valley?) Most of the Second Valley forest is plantation Pinus radiata, at time of writing.

description: Parrot Road Reserve
Gum topped box

I have identified this plant as belonging to the family Myrtaceae because:
- There was a distinct smell to the leaves when crushed
- There were oil glands present in the leaves
- It had a woody trunk
- Its leaves were simple with entire margins
- Flowers were radially symmetrical
- Flowers had numerous, showy stamens
- Flower parts in multiples of 4

I think it is part of the Eucalyptus genus because:
- Its leaves have oil glands, and the scent they produce is distinctly Eucalyptus-like
- Its fruits were gum-nuts (woody capsules)
- It is a tree
- Petals form a cap over the flower, and fall off once the flower opens.

I think this plant is Eucalyptus haemastoma because:
- It is a tree, around 10m tall
- It has smooth bark, grey in colour, with scribbles on it. 
- The buds are clavate in shape, around 6mm long.
- The nuts were conical in shape, around 8mm long. The disks on top are flat and the valves are enclosed. 
- This species’ distribution and occurrence matches the location of this individual (dry sclerophyll woodland on shallow infertile sandy soil, found around the east coast of NSW from Lake Macquarie to the Royal National Park)
